com.lukeleber.scandroid.sae.j1979

Class PIDSupport

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.lukeleber.scandroid.sae.j1979.PIDSupport
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    android.os.Parcelable, java.io.Serializable

    public final class PIDSupport
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.io.Serializable, android.os.Parcelable
    This implementation was created from the information provided through Table A1 of Appendix A of the SAE-J1979 document.

    SAE-J1979 supports querying the PIDs supported by a vehicle in ranges of 32 boolean fields where the last field in the range represents whether or not additional support ranges exist for a provided vehicle. This class encapsulates this support with an easy to use interface that allows querying individual PIDs as well as providing a more advanced way to reap lower level efficiency should it be needed.

      • checkSupport

        public boolean checkSupport(int pid)
        Is the provided PID supported?

        It is worth noting that this method will perform the following conversion on the pid argument to ensure a proper value for this range: 

                 pid %= 32;
        Therefore it is feasible to feed this method semantically incorrect inputs and retrieve a valid result. For example, if this PIDSupport represents support checking for PIDs 1 to 32 and the provided pid argument is 33, while 33 is semantically out of range, it is shifted into range and the result (33 % 32 = 1) is used in the calculation.

        Parameters:
        pid - the PID (in the range [1, 254]) to check support for
        Returns:
        true if the provided PID is supported, otherwise false
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if provided PID lies outside of the range [1, 254]

        Fun fact: PID 0 is required and guaranteed to be supported in all circumstances whereas PID 255 is reserved by the standard and is (currently) required to be unsupported in all circumstances.
